affic">{{cite web |url=https://www.marinetraffic.com/en/ais/details/ships/shipid:187778/mmsi:235005810/imo:9261463/vessel:RACHEL_CARSON |title=Rachel Carson |date=9 October 2017 |website=MarineTraffic.com |access-date=25 November 2018}}</ref> |Ship tonnage={{GT|168}}; {{DWT|50}}<ref name="marinetraffic"/> |Ship displacement= |Ship length={{Convert|22|m|ftin|abbr=on}} [[Length overall|o/a]]<ref name="marinetraffic"/> |Ship beam={{Convert|7.82|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name="marinetraffic"/> |Ship height= |Ship draught={{Convert|3.2|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name="marinetraffic"/> |Ship draft= |Ship depth= |Ship hold depth= |Ship decks= |Ship deck clearance= |Ship power=Diesel direct drive<ref name="unols-cncap">{{cite web |url=https://www.unols.org/sites/default/files/201709cncap_14.pdf |title=R/V Rachel Carson |date=8 September 2017 |website=University of Washington School of Oceanography|access-date=25 November 2018}}</ref> |Ship propulsion=2 shafts, Bow thruster<ref name="UWSO-RVRC"/> |Ship speed={{Convert|10.2|kn|km/h|lk=in}}<ref name="unols-cncap"/> |Ship range= |Ship endurance= |Ship boats= |Ship capacity= |Ship crew= |Ship sensors= |Ship notes= }} |} '''R/V ''Rachel Carson''''' is a [[research vessel]] owned and operated by the [[University of Washington]]'s School of Oceanography, named in honor of the marine biologist and writer [[Rachel Carson]]. The vessel is part of the [[University-National Oceanographic Laboratory System|UNOLS]] fleet. It is capable of conducting operations within the [[Salish Sea]] and coastal waters of the western United States and British Columbia. She can accommodate up to 28 persons, including the crew, for day operations, while up to 13 can be accommodated for multi-day operations.<ref name="UWSO-RVRC"/><ref name="king5-1st-voyage"/>
==Service history==
===R/V ''Aora'', 2003–2016=== The ship was originally launched in May 2003 at the Macduff Shipyard in [[Macduff, Aberdeenshire|Macduff]], Scotland, as the R/V ''Aora'', a [[fisheries research vessel]].<ref name="UWSO-RVRC">{{cite web |url=https://www.ocean.washington.edu/story/RV_Rachel_Carson |title=R/V Rachel Carson |date=2018 |website=University of Washington School of Oceanography |access-date=25 November 2018}}</ref> She was based at the [[University Marine Biological Station Millport]] in the [[Firth of Clyde]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.riverclydephotography.uk/2010/12/rv-aora.html |title=R/V Aora |last=Ward |first=Gerard |date=6 December 2010 |website=River Clyde Photography |access-date=25 November 2018}}</ref> until the station was closed in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.field-studies-council.org/centres/scotland/millport/about/history.aspx |title=Millport History |website=[[Field Studies Council]] |access-date=25 November 2018}}</ref>
===R/V ''Rachel Carson'', 2017–present=== In 2015 the University of Washington's School of Oceanography wanted to replace the fifty-year old {{ship|RV|Clifford A. Barnes}}, but were unable to raise the funds required to design and build a replacement. In December 2016 they found the ''Aora'' for sale on a yacht-trading website.<ref name="king5-1st-voyage">{{cite web |url=https://www.king5.com/article/news/local/uw-launches-1st-voyage-saturday-on-bigger-better-research-ship/281-536058226 |title=UW launches 1st voyage Saturday on bigger, better research ship |last=Farley |first=Glenn |date=6 April 2018 |website=[[KING-TV]] |access-date=25 November 2018 |dead-url=yes |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407042551/https://www.king5.com/article/news/local/uw-launches-1st-voyage-saturday-on-bigger-better-research-ship/281-536058226 |archive-date=7 April 2018}}</ref><ref name="irso.info">{{cite web |url=https://www.irso.info/wp-content/uploads/Russell-RV-Rachel-Carson-Presentation-26-Sept-2018-IRSO-copy.pdf |title=R/V Rachel Carson |first=Doug |last=Russell |date=26 September 2018 |website=International Research Ship Operators |access-date=25 November 2018}}</ref> After an inspection in March 2017, the ship was purchased for $1.07m on 8 August 2017,<ref name="irso.info"/> with the aid of a $1m gift.<ref name="new-uw-vessel">{{cite web |url=http://www.washington.edu/news/2018/05/10/new-uw-vessel-rv-rachel-carson-will-explore-regional-waters/ |title=New UW vessel, RV Rachel Carson, will explore regional waters |last=Hickey |first=Hannah |date=May 10, 2018 |website=UW News |access-date=25 November 2018}}</ref> A programme of maintenance and some modifications at the MacDuff yard were completed in October, and the ''Rachel Carson'' was transported by ship from [[Rotterdam]] to [[West Palm Beach, Florida]] by early November.<ref name="irso.info"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.macduffshipdesign.com/news/the-rachel-carson-transported-to-the-university-of-washington/ |title=The "Rachel Carson" transported to the University of Washington |date=16 December 2017 |website=MacDuff Ship Design |access-date=25 November 2018}}</ref> She was then transported to the University of Washington, arriving on 28 December. After further preparations and modifications the ship entered service on 7 April 2018,<ref name="irso.info"/> with a five-day cruise in [[Puget Sound]] to collect samples for monitoring by the Washington Ocean Acidification Center.<ref name="new-uw-vessel"/> She was accepted as a UNOLS vessel in the U.S. Academic Research Fleet on 24 July.<ref name="irso.info"/>
